# How to Perform a Fire Risk Assessment

Follow along as we show you how to perform a Fire Risk Assessment with the latest version of the RiskBase App. 

\[[Video](https://youtu.be/IRWi2OEjiw8)\]

## Step 1: Open the RiskBase app on your mobile device

Follow our guide [here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1ZRVNE1K8GH-k2GpaUHO8cH53A1N4oh0H9kqf0wtw5AU) to get started.

## Step 2: Open the Fire Risk Assessments for an Asset  

You can find the fire risk assessments for an asset in the ‘Fire Summary’ section:

1. Tap on one of your downloaded assets.  
2. Tap on **Fire Summary**.

![][image1]

3. Press **\+ Create Fire Risk Assessment** and then **select a template**. If you have multiple templates, you'll need to select which to use.

![][image2]

## Step 3: Fill out the checklists and questions  

Assessments are made up of checklists and questions that need to be answered. Checklists and questions have several functions. They are used to:

* Prompt assessors.  
* Identify remedial actions and control measures.  
* Demonstrate to the customer the considerations made during an assessment. 

A checklist is used when there are multiple considerations and contains a list of statements that can be agreed or disagreed with. Checklists are fast and easy to fill out, and define clear options that are easy to understand. 

Questions are used when the answer is not a straightforward yes or no answer and multiple choice is required.

### How to answer a checklist

1. Tap on a checklist. Checklists appear in the Fire Risk Assessment navigation menu with a **C** icon.  
2. Tap the **✓** if you agree with the statement, tap the **✗** if you disagree with the statement or tap the **–** if the statement is not relevant.   
3. Work your way through the list of statements. As you answer the checklists, editable suggestions for actions and control measures will appear below the question. You can select the suggestions by tapping on them, or create new actions and controls. 

![][image3]

### How to answer a question

1. Tap on a question. Questions appear in the Fire Risk Assessment navigation menu with a **Q** icon.  
2. Select one of the multiple-choice answers. When you answer the question, suggestions for actions and control measures will appear below. You can select editable suggestions by tapping on them, or create new actions and controls. 

![][image4]

## Step 4: Add actions and control measures to your answers 

### Adding Actions

For each answer you give in a fire risk assessment, you can suggest an [action](https://riskbase.uk/support/app/actions) that should be taken to remediate an issue. 

The suggestions you added in the Assessment Template for actions will appear below each answer. You can edit a suggestion or [create a custom actions and controls](https://riskbase.uk/support/app/actions#use-custom-actions) if none of the suggestions are appropriate. 

### Using control measure suggestions

Like actions, a list of editable control measure suggestions appears below checklists and questions when they are answered. To use a control measure suggestion:

1. Tap on a control measure suggestion.  
2. Edit the description (if necessary).  
3. Add to the 'why' field to explain why this is required (optional).  
4. Add a location description (optional).  
5. Attach a supporting photo. Take a photo with your device's camera or add a photo from your device's photo library.

## Step 5: Submit a Fire Risk Assessment  

Once you’ve filled in all the required information, submit the fire risk assessment:

1. Scroll to the top of the assessment navigation.  
2. Press **Assessment Overview**.  
3. Press **Submit**.

And that's it\! RiskBase provides an efficient and user friendly way to accurately perform assessments for any kind of survey or inspection.

## Fire Risk Assessment Ttips   

### Don’t lose your data, make sure you remember to sync\!

**Don’t lose your assessment\!** Make sure that after you’ve made any changes to your Riskbase assets that you synchronise them back to the cloud, or you risk losing them. 

##### **Press the green sync button (bottom-right of the screen) to ensure your data is saved in the cloud.**

### Tailor the look and feel of the RiskBase assessment interface.

While you are performing a fire risk assessment, you can change the layout of fields and questions to suit your workflow by updating the list options. 

This lets you do things like showing more list items at once, and hiding completed questions in the list to make filling out assessments faster. 

### How to Change List Options

To change the list options, press the settings icon at the top of the assessment navigation screen. 

The list options will pop up in a modal where you can change the list size, amount of detail displayed, and which questions and checklists should be shown. 

![][image5]

The RiskBase App remembers your preferences while you are signed in. 

When viewing the list options, the yellow dot indicates you have a non-default list option turned on. 

The list options allow you to:

#### Adjust the List Size

Fit more on your screen by switching from normal to small to decrease the text size and amount of space fields and questions take up.

#### Show and Hide List Details

Set the amount of information displayed under each question. 

* Default shows a preview of the actions and controls, along with details of severity, timescale, categories and whether photos are added.   
* Less shows a preview of the actions and controls only.  
* More shows the full action and control text, along with details of severity, timescale, categories and whether photos are added.

#### Hide or Show Questions & Checklists

Hide or show questions and checklists based their status or answer:

* Show Unanswered.  
* Show Negatively Answered.  
* Show Positively Answered.

#### Hide or Show Actions & Controls

* Hide Actions & Controls collapses all the questions. This allows you to see more questions on your screen. Press on a question to expand and see the actions and controls.   
* Show References adds the six digit RiskBase reference.  
* Show New & Reviewed.  
* Show Unreviewed.

![][image6]

## Reviewing a Previous Fire Risk Assessment  

Fire risk reassessments let you review the actions and control measures identified in previous assessments.

During follow-up visits, previous controls, actions and answers appear in the assessment. Actions can then be reviewed as **Not Started**, **In Progress**, **Completed** and **Cancelled**. Control measures can be reviewed as **On-going** or **Cancelled**. 

### How to check and confirm the status of previous actions

Assessors can check and confirm the status of previous actions. To do this, you have to answer the checklist or question the action is linked to first:

1. Press on a greyed out action.  
2. Review the action as **Not started**, **In Progress**, **Completed** or **Cancelled**.  
3. Provide a review note (optional).   
4. Add to or edit the action details (if necessary).

### How to confirm previous control measures are still in place

If existing arrangements have stayed the same, previous control measures can be marked as **Ongoing**. The assessor doesn't need to re-add the same controls during each FRA, saving time.

If the control is no longer valid, assessors can select **Cancelled** to remove it.

## How to Copy aA Fire Risk Assessment  

You can copy in-progress assessments from one asset to another.

If you have a series of similar buildings to assess, this tool will allow you to create a blueprint assessment and copy it to the other buildings.

This may also be useful if you have a customer who wants their actions and controls to include specific language and/or reference their policies.

### How To Copy an Assessment

1. Sign in to [https://app.riskbase.uk](https://app.riskbase.uk/).  
2. Download the asset you are copying from and the asset/s you are copying to.  
3. Press on the asset you want to copy from.  
4. Press **Continue In-Progress Assessment**.  
5. Press the **...** at the top of the screen to show options.  
6. Select **Copy Assessment**.  
7. Select the asset/s you want to copy to.  
8. Press **Copy**.

### What You Need To Know Before Copying An Assessment

* An assessment must be in progress to be copied.  
* An approved assessment cannot be copied.  
* You need to be the author of an assessment to copy it.  
* The copy tool does not copy photos or field information that identifies the building.  
* An assessment can be copied to one or more assets at a time.
